column240: Info:"A rare and beautiful rough cut gorge connecting two of the world's largest bodies of fresh water. There are 2 distinct rock types here offering roofs
column255: fossils and jet black squirrels.  All this within a few klicks of the mighty Niagara Falls.  \r\rThe Niagara Glen experiences all 4 seasons to their fullest relative potentials
column256: so plan accordingly.  (i.e. summer is hot and humid
column259: winter is cold).  \r\rHere you'll find a rather large collection of limestone blocks which have mainly fallen from the headwall above and subsequently come to rest on the Canadian portion of the Niagara Gorge.  There is as well a healthy smattering of sandstone deposited below the limestone layer appearing closer to the river which manifest as both \"cave\" and water-worn egg like blocks
column260: some of which protrude from the gorgeside.  \r\rAn interesting aside: It is thought by some geologists that significant portions of the Niagara River Gorge were cut by the Falls in a mere matter of weeks as the falls crushed their way from lake Ontario towards lake Erie.  Much of the limestone/dolostone here is over 400 million years old and is full of fossil remnants.\r\rThis area
column262: offers a large range of rock quality.  All I can say is that the best lines are quite good.  The grades currently range from v0 to v12 and the usual potentials abound.  It has been said that the moderate grades are better represented here than the harder lines
column263: and while there may be a modicum of truth to this statement
column265: this is likely an outdated sentiment.  Indeed
column266: there are classics at all levels if you know where to look.  \r\rThis being said
column267: the Glen encompasses a somewhat large area covering several kilometers from end to end and while there are a number of dense concentrations
column268: much of the climbing is spread out.  The classics of each grade may be hidden at first but the intrepid will surely reward themselves with quality bouldering and its associated stoke.\r\rAn important word about Access etc: It should be said that the Glen boulders live in a very special climatic zone known as a Carolinian forest (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carolinian_forest) which houses rare plant and animal species protected by the Provincial Nature Preserve in which it resides.  The Niagara Glen is apparently home to some of the only remaining Carolinian Forest in all of Canada. Local climbers have worked exceedingly hard with land managers to secure access to the bouldering in exchange for some basic behavior modifications.  These modifications largely revolve around common sense as it applies to delicate organisms in addition to other user groups (see \"Access Information/Issues\" to the left) and should be explored further via the Ontario Access Coalition website (www.ontarioaccesscoalition.com) prior to visiting the area."
column349: Info:"Rock is smooth quarzitic sandstone. Routes mostly short and brutally powerful. Warming up is difficult
column350: try traversing in cave below Cling thing to warm up. 'Power drain' usually ends your session after a few goes! Rock gets slippery very quickly in humid conditions or when the SE wind is blowing strongly (summer). Best season is Autumn (May - June). Some routes seep water in winter. Despite its drawbacks this crag holds more hard projects than any other in Cape Town."

column13354: 1/3 is on mixed protection and the final 1/3 is on natural protection.\r\rFood and accommodation;\rEttringen has little to offer. Both Eifelperle and 'Grillstube' have closed down. column13355: Laacher See). \r\rSeason:\rIt's possible to climb all year round as long as it is dry. Winter is best for hard routes and can offer surprisingly good conditions in the sun on the relatively warm dark grey rock. Summer is for softmovers

column14963: Info:"Extensive area with over 800 cliffs and more than 11.500 routes. Most of them on steep and pocketed limestone. Routes cover anything from 10 m steep bouldery powerfests to 40 m long vertical routes.\r\rThe best time to go is late spring (May and June) or fall (September and October). Winters are cold with snow from December until February. Summers are either warm (30C) and dry or rainy. But you can find enough shady places for the hot summer days because a lot of crags are in the woods.\r\rSeveral excellent camping sites can be found. Pottenstein for example. Climb when you exit your tent
column14964: cos the Bärenschluchtwände are at the campsite itself!\r\rThe meeting point for climbers is the campground in Untertrubach
column14965: opposite of the Zehnerstein. Everybody knows it as Oma Eichler. Obviously you can camp here. There are several other campsites in the neighbourhood. Cheap accomodation (appartments or local guesthouses) are easy to find.\r\rIn the lower grades (up to 6b) the protection is not good. Although there are some good exceptions. And using nuts and friends can be fun.\r\rA guidebook and a road map/satnav system for the area are essential to get the most out of your time here. Kletterführer Frankenjura Band 1 and Band 2 from Sebastian Schwertner/Panico Verlag cover the whole area. Frankenjura Extreme from the same author in English is a selected guidebook with more than 2000 routes mostly in the harder grades above 7a. All books are for sale at the Campground Eichler in Untertrubach
